<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Body length: male 16 mm (based on 
<bibRefCitation author="Sack, P" journalOrPublisher="A catalogue of the Diptera of the Americas south of the United States" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B30" refString="Sack, P, 1921. Dr. L. Zuercher's Dipteran-Ausbeute aus Paraguay: Syrphiden. Archiv fuer Naturgeschichte 87(A): 127-149." title="Dr. L. Zuercher's Dipteran-Ausbeute aus Paraguay: Syrphiden. Archiv fuer Naturgeschichte 87 (A): 127 - 149." year="1921">Sack 1921</bibRefCitation>
), female 16.5-18.5. The constricted abdomen, absence of a triangle of golden pile on the mesoscutum, and partly dark wings place 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. diaphanus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="diaphanus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. diaphanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in a group with 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. elongatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="elongatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. elongatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. hermetia" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="hermetia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. hermetia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. hermetoides" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="hermetoides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. hermetoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Reemer, 2013" authorityName="Reemer" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Peradon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Peradon diaphanus" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diaphanus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Peradon diaphanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from the other three species by tergite 2 being longer than wide, and also by the rufous golden pilose mesoscutum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Pape, T" journalOrPublisher="Conservation Genetics" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" publicationUrl="http://www.diptera.org/" refId="B20" refString="Pape, T, Thompson, FC, 2013. .http://www.diptera.org/" url="http://www.diptera.org/" year="2013">Pape and Thompson (2013)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.288.4095" author="Reemer, M" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 213" refId="B25" refString="Reemer, M, Stahls, G, 2013a. Generic revision and species classification of the Microdontinae (Diptera, Syrphidae). ZooKeys 288: 1 - 213" title="Generic revision and species classification of the Microdontinae (Diptera, Syrphidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.288.4095" volume="288" year="2013 a">
Reemer and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Ståhls">Stahls</normalizedToken>
(2013a)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.49898" author="Thompson, FC" journalOrPublisher="A catalogue of the Diptera of the Americas south of the United States" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 195" refId="B29" refString="Thompson, FC, Vockeroth, JR, Sedman, YS, 1976. Family Syrphidae. A catalogue of the Diptera of the Americas south of the United States 46: 1 - 195" title="Family Syrphidae." url="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.49898" volume="46" year="1976">Thompson et al. (1976)</bibRefCitation>
, the type of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Microdon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Microdon diaphanus" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diaphanus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Microdon diaphanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is deposited in the DEI (
<normalizedToken originalValue="Müncheberg">Muencheberg</normalizedToken>
). However, attempts to find it in that collection failed (pers. comm. F. Menzel). The DEI is part of the Senckenberg research institute, which also holds entomological collections in Dresden (SNSD) and Frankfurt (SMF). Enquiries at these institutions did not result in finding the type either. As a large part of the collection of P. Sack was destroyed during World War II (
<bibRefCitation author="Franz, E" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B7" refString="Franz, E, 1967. Geschichte der Entomologischen Sekstion. Senckenbergiana Biologica 48(B): 55-72." title="Geschichte der Entomologischen Sekstion. Senckenbergiana Biologica 48 (B): 55 - 72." year="1967">Franz 1967</bibRefCitation>
), it seems probable that this has also happened to the type of 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. diaphanus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="diaphanus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. diaphanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In order to ensure the stability of this taxon, a neotype designation is deemed desirable. One female from Brazil (coll. NHMUK) and three females from Paraguay (coll. USNM) agree well with the original description and the figure in 
<bibRefCitation author="Sack, P" journalOrPublisher="A catalogue of the Diptera of the Americas south of the United States" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B30" refString="Sack, P, 1921. Dr. L. Zuercher's Dipteran-Ausbeute aus Paraguay: Syrphiden. Archiv fuer Naturgeschichte 87(A): 127-149." title="Dr. L. Zuercher's Dipteran-Ausbeute aus Paraguay: Syrphiden. Archiv fuer Naturgeschichte 87 (A): 127 - 149." year="1921">Sack (1921)</bibRefCitation>
. As the species was originally described from Paraguay, one of the Paraguayan females is here designated as neotype.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The three females from Paraguay are mounted together with empty puparia and carry labels stating &quot;ex ant colony in arboreal bromelia&quot;. This is the first known record of an association of a 
<taxonomicName authority="Reemer, 2013" authorityName="Reemer" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Peradon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Peradon" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Peradon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species with ants. Unfortunately, the ants remain unidentified.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Known from the Brazilian state 
<normalizedToken originalValue="São">Sao</normalizedToken>
Paulo and from Paraguay.
</paragraph>
